Satellite attitude control is maintained in part by magnetotorquers, which use pulses of electric current to generate magnetic moments through which the geomagnetic field imparts additional angular momentum to the satellite depending on the sign and magnitude of the current pulse. The magnetic field generated by the magnetotorquers imparts a small change to the velocity of the incoming ions via the Lorentz force. Using field values estimated by ESA for a maximum expected magnetotorquer current of 0.1 A, the maximum ion drift error magnitude is 18 m/s worst case and 12 m/s (1σ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
